<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-035-174 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 475 047</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Oct 14 1991 n342 p18(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Planes, trains, and systems. (Conrail program uses MIS to take onthe trucking industry) (MIS at Consolidated Rail Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caldwell, Bruce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Consolidated Rail Corp VP of Information Services (IS) Robert O.andO;Wagner plans to overhaul IS at the $3.4 billion Philadelphia-basedrailway firm.andP;  Wagner, who left Pan Am to join Conrail in May1991, has signed a contract with Andersen Consulting to buy $1million in computer-aided software engineering (CASE) tools.andO;Wagner manages an annual budget of $95 million and a staff of 600.andO;The Conrail board of directors recently approved $35 million toreplace two data centers with one disaster-resistant center.andP;  Theoverhaul of IS is part of an effort to battle growing competitionfrom the trucking industry, which has made good use of such newtechnologies as electronic data interchange (EDI) and satellitecommunications.andP;  In addition, Conrail is working with otherrailway firms to develop data exchange standards and to placesensors along tracks to pick up signals from radio frequency tagson passing rail cars.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Consolidated Rail Corp. (Communication systems).andO;Topic:     Information systemsRailroad IndustryAutomationMISCompetitionStandardizationComputer-Aided Software Engineering.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Robert O. Wagner. (portrait)Person:    Wagner, Robert O. (Management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>